<h2 id="cocoa-crisis">The Cocoa Crisis Changes Everything</h2>

<p>For decades, Ghana's agricultural identity has been synonymous with cocoa. The country is the world's second-largest producer, and cocoa has been the default mental model for anyone thinking about Ghanaian agriculture. That model just broke.</p>

<div class="data-box">
  <h4>Cocoa Crisis: Key Numbers</h4>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Indicator</th><th>Before</th><th>Now</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>World cocoa price</td><td>$8,000+/tonne (2024 peak)</td><td>$3,500-4,100/tonne (March 2026)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Cocobod producer price</td><td>GHS 58,000/tonne (~$5,286)</td><td>GHS 41,392/tonne (~$3,771)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Farmer payments (Nov-Dec 2025)</td><td>Expected</td><td>Unpaid as of Feb 2026</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p><strong>Source:</strong> Cocobod official pricing, ICCO world market data [WEB-FRESH 2026-03-27]</p>
  <p><strong>GhanaWorld verdict: Cocoa sub-sector is AVOID FOR NEW ENTRY.</strong></p>
</div>

<p>The collapse is not a temporary dip. World cocoa prices surged to historic highs in 2024 on supply shortages from West Africa, then crashed as speculative positions unwound and demand adjusted. Cocobod, Ghana's cocoa marketing board, cut the producer price by 29%. Farmers who delivered beans in November and December 2025 had not been paid as of February 2026.</p>

<p>But here is what the cocoa crisis obscures: Ghana's agriculture is 19% of GDP. Agriculture grew 5.3% in Q4 2025. The sector that matters for investors and entrepreneurs is not cocoa; it is everything else.</p>

