<h2 id="cassava">Cassava Processing: The Bakery Supply Chain</h2>

<p>Ghana has a large, active, commercially legible bakery ecosystem. Bakeries are highly sensitive to flour prices. High-Quality Cassava Flour (HQCF) can substitute 10-30% of imported wheat flour in bread, reducing cost and import dependence.</p>

<p>The opportunity is processing cassava into HQCF and selling to bakeries as a cost-saving flour substitute. The market structure is visible: named bakeries, documented flour consumption patterns, and price sensitivity data from GhanaWorld's field research.</p>

<div class="risk-box">
  <h4>Cassava Processing: What Can Kill This Business</h4>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Raw material inconsistency:</strong> Smallholder cassava supply varies in quality, moisture content, and timeliness. Without structured procurement (aggregation centres, quality testing, advance contracts), your factory sits idle. (FP-005)</li>
    <li><strong>Power costs:</strong> Processing requires consistent electricity. Generator backup is not optional; it is a structural operating cost. Budget GHS 15,000-25,000/month ($1,370-2,280) for fuel. (FP-003)</li>
    <li><strong>Working capital:</strong> You buy cassava roots before you sell flour. The cash cycle is 30-60 days. Without 90-120 day reserves, one delayed payment from a bakery buyer kills you. (FP-006)</li>
    <li><strong>Bakery buyer discipline:</strong> Some bakeries pay late or switch suppliers for small price differences. Named anchor buyers secured before launch are essential.</li>
  </ul>
  <p><strong>Confidence:</strong> HIGH (based on 40+ cycles of analysis)</p>
</div>

<p>The cassava opportunity scored 6.65/10 after arithmetic verification in Cycle 021. That is a genuine, evidence-grounded score, not a rounded-up number. It reflects real market demand with real execution barriers.</p>

<h2 id="shea">Shea Butter: The Export Certification Play</h2>

<p>Ghana's northern regions produce significant shea nut volumes. The global shea butter market serves cosmetics, food, and pharmaceutical industries. The opportunity is processing raw shea nuts into refined or semi-refined butter for export markets, particularly the EU.</p>

<p>The critical lesson from GhanaWorld's analysis: certification is an investment, not a compliance burden. The EU's EUDR (Deforestation Regulation) requires documented traceability from source to export. Operators who start certification documentation on Day 1 gain a durable competitive advantage over those who defer it.</p>

