<p>Shea requires northern Ghana networks. A diaspora founder without existing relationships in the Upper West, Upper East, or Northern regions faces a significant trust and logistics barrier. This is not a business you can start from Accra.</p>

<h2 id="oil-palm">Oil Palm: The $2B Import Gap</h2>

<p>Ghana imports over $2 billion in vegetable oils annually, mostly palm oil. Domestic production is approximately 300,000 tonnes against demand exceeding 500,000 tonnes. The government has launched a national oil palm development programme targeting 100,000 hectares and 250,000 jobs.</p>

<p>The opportunity is real but slow. Oil palm trees take 3-4 years to reach commercial maturity. The capital requirement is high ($200,000+ minimum for a meaningful plantation). Land tenure risk in rural areas is significant (FP-007). This is a long-term play that suits patient, well-capitalised investors, not lean startups.</p>

<p>GhanaWorld's pre-screening score of 5.8-6.2/10 reflects genuine potential constrained by timeline, capital intensity, and land risk. See our dedicated <a href="/analysis/oil-palm-opportunity">Oil Palm opportunity brief</a> for the full analysis.</p>

<h2 id="rice-poultry">Rice and Poultry: Import Substitution Limits</h2>

<p>Both rice and poultry are commonly cited as Ghana investment opportunities. Both have real demand. Both have structural problems that make them unsuitable for most diaspora investors.</p>

<p><strong>Rice:</strong> Ghana imports significant volumes of rice. Domestic production is constrained by irrigation infrastructure (most rice farming is rain-fed), seed quality, and post-harvest losses. The government has made rice self-sufficiency a stated goal through multiple administrations without achieving it. The capital requirement for irrigated rice farming is $300,000+ for a commercially meaningful operation. Diaspora classification: Not-Diaspora-Suitable.</p>

<p><strong>Poultry:</strong> Ghana's poultry industry faces a structural disadvantage: feed (maize, soya) is partially imported, creating cedi-denominated revenue against dollar-linked input costs (FP-002). Cheap frozen imports from Brazil and the US undercut domestic producers on price. Disease risk (avian influenza) adds biological uncertainty. Capital requirement: $150,000+ for a meaningful operation. Diaspora classification: Not-Diaspora-Suitable.</p>

<div class="risk-box">
  <h4>Why Rice and Poultry Score Below 5.0</h4>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Infrastructure dependency:</strong> Both require reliable power, water, and cold chain that Ghana's rural areas cannot consistently provide</li>
    <li><strong>Import competition:</strong> Cheap imports set a price ceiling that domestic producers struggle to match</li>
    <li><strong>Currency mismatch:</strong> Feed and input costs linked to USD; revenue in GHS (FP-002)</li>
    <li><strong>Capital intensity:</strong> Minimum viable scale requires $150,000-300,000+</li>
    <li><strong>Presence requirement:</strong> Both require daily on-ground management; cannot be run remotely</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<h2 id="government-investment">Government Investment: What Is Real</h2>

<p>The Mahama administration has announced GHS 1.7 billion (~$155 million at GHS/USD 10.97) in agricultural investment: seven processing plants and 1,000 kilometres of rural roads. Additionally, a free fertiliser programme has been announced.</p>

<div class="risk-box">
  <h4>Policy Announcement vs. Implementation (FP-004)</h4>
  <p>Ghana has a documented pattern of announced agricultural policies with delayed or zero implementation. The 1D1F (One District, One Factory) programme under the previous administration delivered a fraction of its stated targets. Planting for Food and Jobs had mixed results.</p>
  <p><strong>GhanaWorld's rule:</strong> Do not base business viability on government investment promises until implementation evidence exists. If your business model only works because a government-funded road or factory materialises, you do not have a business model.</p>
  <p><strong>Confidence in GHS 1.7B delivery:</strong> LOW (announced, no implementation evidence yet)</p>
</div>

<p>The free fertiliser programme is a fiscal commitment, not a market signal. It increases government spending obligations during a period when fiscal discipline is critical (IMF exit in August 2026). Founders should monitor whether the programme creates genuine agricultural productivity gains or becomes a fiscal drain.</p>

